Problem 6.
 Angrist problems 3-15 and 3-16
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(3-15) Find the electrical resistivity for the material described in problem
 3-8(b)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The material in 3-8(b) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ce{InSb}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $400\unit{K}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{17}\unit{cm^{-3}}$
\end_inset

 charge carrier density, with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{n}=m_{p}$
\end_inset

 and mobility of the electrons 
\begin_inset Formula $40,000\unit{\frac{cm^{2}}{Vs}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resitivity is given as the reciprocal of the conductivity, or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\equiv\frac{1}{\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

where the conductivity is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=ne\mu
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the charge carrier density, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the electron charge, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the mobility of the electrons.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho & =\frac{1}{ne\mu}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\left(10^{17}\unit{\frac{1}{cm^{3}}}\right)\left(1.6\times10^{-19}\unit{C}\right)\left(40,000\unit{\frac{cm^{2}}{Vs}}\right)}\\
 & =0.001563\unit{\Omega\cdot cm}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Doubling this to account for the hole mobility as well, we get
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This matches exactly the value given by Angrist.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho=3.1\times10^{-3}\unit{\Omega\cdot cm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(3-16) Find the electrical conductivity for the material given in Problem
 3-12 if it has a hole mobility of 
\begin_inset Formula $60\unit{\frac{cm^{2}}{Vs}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conductivity is given as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=ne\mu
\]

\end_inset

 and with the charge carrier density as given earlier, the hole mobility
 from the problem, and the electron charge, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma & =\left(1.5\times10^{18}\right)\left(1.6\times10^{-19}\unit{C}\right)\left(60\unit{\frac{cm^{2}}{Vs}}\right)\\
 & =14.4\unit{\frac{1}{\Omega\cdot cm}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

